    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i've heard about pH being important but i dont really get the science behind it. like, if the soil is too alkaline, does the iron just disappear? how does the chemistry actually stop the plant from absorbing it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The chemistry behind pH and nutrient absorption is quite fascinating. When soil pH is too high, it can lead to a phenomenon called \"chelate formation.\" Chelates are compounds that bind to nutrients, making them unavailable to the plant. In the case of iron, high pH levels can form iron oxides, which are essentially iron particles that are no longer soluble and therefore not available to the plant. This is why blueberries, which require iron, can become iron-deficient in alkaline soils.",
      "source": "target",
